# Lenar Materials Architecture Rule

This workspace uses a mandatory dual model for each domain under `docs/`:
- `topics/` for canonical topic content (source of truth).
- `learning/`, `cheatsheets/`, `recipes/` for usage modes; для **Linux** страницы команд — в верхнеуровневом `core-commands/` (см. ниже), а не внутри `cheatsheets/`.

## Core Intent
- Build practical reference materials for different audiences.
- Keep content easy to navigate by both topic and consumption mode.
- Prevent duplication as the project grows.

## Required Structure For Every Domain
- `docs/<domain>/README.md`
- `docs/<domain>/topics/<topic>/README.md`
- `docs/<domain>/learning/*.md`
- `docs/<domain>/cheatsheets/*.md` (для доменов вроде SQL; у **Linux** каталог `cheatsheets/` не используется для подробных команд)
- `docs/<domain>/recipes/*.md`
- для **Linux** дополнительно: `docs/linux/tips/*.md` — **Tips & Tricks**; `docs/linux/core-commands/*.md` — **Core Commands** (один файл на команду + `README.md` — индекс; верхний уровень домена, без вложения в `cheatsheets/`). Порядок как в меню MkDocs: Topics → Learning → Tips & Tricks → Core Commands → Recipes
- для **SQL** «основы» могут быть разнесены на несколько соседних модулей в `topics/` (например `query-structure/`, `null-and-uniqueness/`, …) плюс обзор `topics/basics/README.md`; каждый модуль — отдельный `README.md` с «Где использовать».

## Authoring Rules
- Put full canonical reference content in `topics/*` (not stubs).
- In `learning/`, `cheatsheets/` (или `core-commands/` для Linux), `recipes/`, keep focused summaries and link back to `topics/*`.
- Each `topics/<topic>/README.md` must include a "Где использовать" section with links to related mode files.
- Prefer links over copied text when overlapping content appears.

## Growth Rules
- Add new domains using the same folder contract.
- Add new topics as new `topics/<topic>/README.md` modules.
- Keep naming stable and descriptive; avoid ad-hoc files in domain root.
- Update `docs/PROJECT_APPROACHES.md` when architecture-level decisions change.
- Track domain-level topics quality findings and remediation backlog in dedicated internal audit documents.

## Default Agent Behavior On Content Requests
- If user asks to "add a new topic" for a domain, create:
  - `<domain>/topics/<topic>/README.md`
  - At least one related mode file update in `learning/`, `cheatsheets/` (или `core-commands/` для Linux), or `recipes/` with links.
- If user asks to "add content", update canonical explanation in `topics/*` first, then add or update mode-specific summaries.
- Always preserve bidirectional linking:
  - `topics/*` -> "Где использовать" -> mode files
  - mode files -> "См. тематические источники" -> `topics/*`
- Prefer extending existing files before creating new files for near-duplicate scope.

## Markdown Content Contract
- For `topics/*` pages (reference mode), keep content compact and reference-first. Do not require instructional flow sections.
- `topics/*` pages should include, when applicable:
  - `# Title`
  - `## Цель`
  - `## Примеры`
  - `## Частые ошибки`
  - `## Связанные материалы`
  - `## Где использовать`
- For `learning/*` pages, instructional structure is allowed and encouraged, including:
  - `## Когда использовать`
  - `## Пошаговый подход`
  - `## Проверка результата`
- Keep pages practical and concise; avoid long theory dumps without examples.

## Per-Command Detail Pages (`core-commands/`)
Use this pattern when a domain stores **one page per command** under `docs/<domain>/core-commands/` (example: `docs/linux/core-commands/pwd.md`), plus **`core-commands/README.md`** as an index.

### Wiring (when adding or changing a command page)
- Link from the domain commands index / compact list (`docs/<domain>/core-commands/README.md`) to each detail page.
- Register the page in `mkdocs.yml` (для Linux — группа **Core Commands**; для других областей — **Cheatsheets**, если так принято для домена).
- Update `core-commands/README.md` to list the command.
- Preserve bidirectional links with relevant `topics/*` (for example add or keep entries under **Где использовать** on related topic pages).
- Keep `content.code.copy` enabled in `mkdocs.yml` (Material: copy button on fenced code blocks).

### Required outline (heading order)
Use this skeleton unless a command truly needs an extra subsection **inside** `## Поведение и параметры`:
1. `# <command>`
2. `## Назначение`
3. `## TLDR` — short invocations only; format like Linux Command Library: one short Russian description line, then a **separate** fenced `bash` block with the command (often one line) so readers can copy cleanly; comments inside code blocks should be short and in Russian where they help.
4. `## Синтаксис`
5. `## Поведение и параметры` — **single** coherent section: explain behavior once; put flags/options in tables here; do **not** duplicate the same explanations across separate sections such as “Описание”, “Основные параметры”, and “Ограничения” unless they add genuinely new information.
6. `## Примеры` — типичные сценарии и команды.

Nested `###` headings under `## Поведение и параметры` are allowed when the command naturally splits (for example “проверки” vs “действия” for `find`).

### Language and anti-noise rules
- Primary language for prose: **Russian**. Prefer plain Russian phrasing over decorative English abbreviations when they do not add clarity (for example avoid unexplained “CWD”, “login name”, “POSIX” stacks; say what you mean in Russian).
- **No redundant repetition**: `## TLDR` shows minimal examples; `## Поведение и параметры` explains meaning and flags **once**—do not restate the same flag semantics in multiple places.

### Default agent behavior
- When the user asks to add or normalize per-command pages, follow this section and match the tone/structure of existing approved examples in `docs/linux/core-commands/` (for example `pwd.md`).

## Build And Publish Contract
- Markdown is the source of truth. Do not manually maintain parallel HTML copies.
- Use MkDocs Material workflow:
  - local preview: `mkdocs serve`
  - build: `mkdocs build`
  - publish: GitHub Actions workflow for Pages
- **Site styling** lives in `docs/stylesheets/extra.css` (linked from `mkdocs.yml`). It controls compact typography and code-block layout.
- **Fenced code blocks in HTML:** default MkDocs output is `<pre><code class="language-…">…</code></pre>` — there is often **no** `div.highlight` wrapper. Rules that target only `.highlight` may apply to nothing. Style **`.md-content .md-typeset pre`** (and optionally `div.highlight` if an extension adds it). Max width for code blocks is tunable via CSS variable `--lenar-code-block-max-width` in `:root` in `extra.css`.

## Public Navigation Contract
- Public docs navigation should expose learning materials only.
- Keep internal process docs (for example: `PROJECT_APPROACHES.md`, `CONTENT_WORKFLOW.md`, and audit/backlog docs) excluded from published site navigation.
- Domain entries should use domain index pages (`docs/<domain>/README.md`) as the clickable entry.
- Under each domain: `Topics`, `Learning`, `Recipes` as nested groups; cheatsheet-style pages live under `Cheatsheets` (например SQL) или для Linux — верхние пункты **Tips & Tricks** (`tips/…`) и **Core Commands** (`core-commands/`), без лишней вложенности в nav.
- Domain submenu groups should be collapsed by default unless user explicitly asks otherwise.
